The standard practice in django apps is to ship JS files inside the static/ dir, which then are collected automatically when one runs manage.py collectstatic. 

if we want to retain the possibility to load from CDN we could add do something like:
```python
    if(getattr(settings, 'DJANGO_HSTORE_UNDERSCOREJS_CDN', False)):
        underscorejs = "//cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/underscore.js/1.5.2/underscore-min.js
    else:
        underscorejs = "django_hstore/underscore-min.js"
```

Do you have data from the other CLIs on what the distribution is between customers that use the "file" option to specify everything in a JSON file vice those who actually use the 30+ arguments?

To me, the sheer number of arguments possible for some of the creates is overwhelming. If you had data on which ones (if any) could be suppressed or deferred to an update step, you could remove or default them to make the usability easier. You can always add those arguments later if people are demanding them, but removing arguments later will be much harder.

