Hey Nick, sorry for the late response.

We are currently discussing an entirely different approach to solving this problem that would require almost no API changes and would add no additional overhead in the embedded case.

The idea is to make the API context stateful by introducing the following new API calls:

```
struct otInstancePrivate;
typedef struct otInstancePrivate otInstance;

/// Initializes the given instance.
/** Returns the required size of the instance. The instance
 *  is only initialized if the return value is greater than or equal
 *  to aInstanceSize. */
ssize_t otInstanceInit(otInstance *aInstance, ssize_t aInstanceSize);

/// Finalize the given instance.
/** Called when the instance is no longer needed. */
void otInstanceFinalize(otInstance *aInstance);

/// Sets the current instance for this thread.
/** Must be called before any API calls are made on a given thread.
 *  On embedded systems that only ever have one instance, this
 *  call is a no-op. */
void otInstanceSet(otInstance *aInstance);

/// Gets the current instance for this thread.
/** Returns the instance previously set on the current thread with
 *  otInstanceSet(). Returns NULL if otInstanceSet() was never called
 *  on the given thread. On embedded systems, this function always
 *  returns the global instance. */
otInstance* otInstanceGet(void);
```

This approach requires thread-local storage if you want your platform to support multiple independent OpenThread instances. What's nice is that for platforms where support for multiple independent instances is not required, the additional overhead is minimal (and can even be made zero with some preprocessor macros).

So, the question then becomes: does the windows kernel allow for thread-local storage in device drivers?

